            <p>Myths of origin
                Myths of origin represent an attempt to render the universe comprehensible in human terms. 
                Greek creation myths (cosmogonies) and views of the universe (cosmologies) were more systematic 
                and specific than those of other ancient peoples. Yet their very artistry serves as an impediment 
                to interpretation, since the Greeks embellished the myths with folktale and fiction told for its 
                own sake. Thus, though the aim of Hesiod's Theogony is to describe the ascendancy of Zeus 
                (and, incidentally, the rise of the other gods), the inclusion of such familiar themes as 
                the hostility between the generations, the enigma of woman (Pandora), the exploits of the 
                friendly trickster (Prometheus), and the struggles against powerful beings or monsters like 
                the Titans (and, in later tradition, the Giants) enhances the interest of an epic account.</p><br>
